title: For Sale:  Surefire P116 light for Beretta 92 & clones WITHOUT RAILS
postcontent:
This is an older Surefire weapons light designed to fit Beretta 92/96 and Taurus clones that don't have a built-in rail.  The light comes with its own rail that attaches to the front of the trigger guard.  

The housing of this lightweight two-battery, 6-volt SureFire P 116 pistol flashlight system is constructed of Nitrolon, a proprietary polymer that is impact and corrosion-resistant. The shock-isolated bezel is constructed of aerospace grade aluminum with a super-hard MilSpec Type III anodized finish. A side-by-side battery housing keeps the Surefire Beretta flashlight P101 system compact, and like all SureFire Weapon-Lights, the bezel and lamp assembly are shock isolated to withstand repeated recoil. SureFire Nitrolon P-Series Beretta Hand Gun Weapon-Lights produce 65 lumens of light for one hour with the standard P60 high-output lamp, or 120 lumens of light for 20 minutes with the P61 ultra-high output lamp assembly.

This is a used weapons light.  At some point someone did something to the Pyrex lens, which blurs the light beam a little, but not enough to matter (picture of beam available).  The grip switch also doesn't work, but the manual switch is perfectly located to be operated by either the trigger finger or the offhand thumb. Otherwise the light is in outstanding shape, with very few handling marks.  Installation requires certification in the operation of a screwdriver to tighten four screws.  That simple.

title: For Sale:  Funny how time changes things
postcontent:
We, yep, you and me, we just kind of ramble down this pathway we call life. We have collected a few gems as we traveled, made by names like Smith & Wesson, Ruger, Colt, Glock & Sig, just to name a few.
Now as we occupy that ole rocker on the front porch and think of the struggles we have had, it comes to mind, thoughts of that gun I alway wanted, but couldn't afford, after all, I had mouths to feed and a mortgage to pay. Now I sit here with a pocket full of money, and all I see are over priced guns, used guns at new cost values, and the same ads, listed day after day, by the same folks just hoping someone new and unknowing will happen by.

Yep, me and this ole rocker have traveled a long way, and seen a lot, but along the way we got smarter, they call that experience, I think. But, I think I'll just keep this pocket full of money, after all, I got experience now to guide my decisions of what to buy.
